        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;When the price of a luxury consumer item is &#163;\({@a@}\), a market survey reveals that the demand is {@b@} items per year. However another survey has shown that at a price of &#163;\({@c@}\), the demand for the item is {@d@} items per year. Assuming that both surveys are valid, find a linear function that relates demand \(Q\) to price \(P\). What demand would be predicted by the linear function at a price of &#163;\({@e@}\) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]]and a price of &#163;500? [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]][[feedback:prt2]]&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Comment on the validity of both predictions.&lt;/p&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;p&gt;The linear function will be of the form:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Q = aP + b &lt;/em&gt;    ({@c@}&#8804;&lt;em&gt;P&lt;/em&gt;&#8804;{@a@})&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The limits on P represent the given range of data on price. Substituting the  values of &lt;em&gt;Q&lt;/em&gt; and &lt;em&gt;P&lt;/em&gt; to calculate the gradient:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;\(\dfrac{{@d@} - {@b@}}{{@c@} - {@a@}}\)&lt;p&gt; = {@m@}&lt;/p&gt;
This can be substituted into the equation &lt;em&gt;Q = aP + b &lt;/em&gt;, using one of the pairs of data, eg.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; {@b@} = {@m@} * {@a@} + &lt;em&gt;b&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This can be rearranged to give:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;em&gt;b&lt;em&gt; = {@y@}&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Therefore the equation of the function is:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Q&lt;/em&gt; = {@m@} * &lt;em&gt;P&lt;/em&gt; + {@y@}&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A precautionary check is to make sure that this result is consistent with the other pairs of values. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Q&lt;/em&gt; = {@m@} * {@c@} + {@y@} = {@d@}&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This is the same as quoted in the question therefore all calculations are correct up to this point.&lt;/p&gt;
To find the demand with a price of &#163;{@e@} we can substitute the values in.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Q = {@m@} * {@e@} + {@y@} = {@ta1@}&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This value is within the two values the market survey found, therefore interpolation is being used, this would suggest that this is a valid prediction. This comes with a caveat however such as the assumption it is a linear function. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If we were to use this model further to predict the demand with a price of &#163;500, we would have to use extreme caution as it is outside our study parameters and therefore we would be extrapolating. 
&lt;p&gt;Q = {@m@} * 500 + {@y@} = {@ta2@}&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If the given data points are close to each other then interpolation between these points is more reliable than extrapolation to points further away.</generalfeedback>
